CONTAMINATED HEROIN - USA (NORTHEAST): ALERT
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 11 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New York City Department of Health & Mental Hygiene Health
Alert 10 Feb 2005 [edited]
[This Health Alert to health care providers was released 10 Feb 2005
by the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene (DOHMH) of New York
City. ProMED-mail was given permission to post this alert by the
DOHMH. - Mod.MPP]

2005 Health Alert #6: Investigation of Tainted Heroin
------------------
Beginning 28 Jan 2005 several male heroin users presented to
hospitals in New Jersey and Pennsylvania complaining of unusual
effects including agitation, nausea, headache, and weakness after
nasal insufflation of heroin. Initial findings by health care
providers were notable for hypotension, tachycardia, hypokalemia and
severe lactic acidosis with an elevated pVO2. Although these findings
were suggestive of cyanide poisoning, subsequent testing failed to
identify cyanide and confirmed clenbuterol in several specimens.
Clenbuterol is an illicit, long-acting beta adrenergic agonist that
is used primarily for increasing lean body mass in cattle. Humans
occasionally use clenbuterol as part of exercise training to increase
endurance and reduce body fat.
A working case definition includes hypokalemia, hyperglycemia ,
metabolic acidosis with an elevated lactate and an elevated venous
PO2. To date multiple cases have been confirmed in New Jersey and
Pennsylvania and several cases are suspected in Connecticut.
The NYC DOHMH now has reports of several patients in NYC meeting the
case definition. A total of 6 cases have reported as of 9 Feb 2005 in
New York City. Since 6 Feb 2005, 4 adult male patients were
evaluated at a hospital in Brooklyn, NY, for hypotension, tachycardia
and hypokalemia. All were attempting to use heroin intranasally.
Shortly after use, all developed anxiety and palpitations; one
developed chest pain. 2 cases were also reported on 8 Feb 2005 from
a Bronx, NY hospital with tachycardia, hypotension, hypokalemia and
palpitations. Most patients can be treated with volume replacement,
but when symptoms are severe and there are no contraindications (such
as recent cocaine use or reversible airways disease) short-acting
parenteral beta adrenergic antagonists can be administered.
For technical assistance in the management of such patients 24 hours
a day, contact the DOHMH's poison control center at 1-800-222-1222.
To assist us in this investigation:
- Report all patients who might meet the case definition to the New
York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene pursuant to Section
11.03 of the New York City Health Code by calling the Poison Control
Center at 212-764-7667 or 1-800-222-1222.
- Submit any suspect material found on patients to the New York City
Police Department for further testing by calling 911 or the local
precinct.
--
