Date: 10 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: 1010 WINS [edited]
<http://1010wins.com/topstories/local_story_041150827.html>

Drug addicts beware
-----------------
3 apparent heroin overdose deaths in New Britain [Connecticut]
prompted a statewide health alert Thursday about a possible bad batch
of the drug in New Jersey and elsewhere in the Northeast.
The Connecticut Poison Control Center, which tracks drug deaths,
issued the advisory after learning 2 men had been found dead in a New
Britain home 3 Feb 2005 and a 3rd in a parking lot on Saturday. The 3
were between the ages of 30 and 50.
"It's unusual to see a clump of heroin deaths, because typically
people who do heroin know how much to give themselves to make
themselves high," said Amy Hanoian-Fontana, a community education
specialist with the center, which is based at the University of
Connecticut Health Center.
New Britain officials have asked workers at hospitals, methadone
clinics and homeless shelters to alert users about the possible bad
heroin.
"The concern is that this is connected to contamination in the
heroin, not just a routine heroin overdose, although we don't know
that yet," said Dr. Eugene Ciccone, director of the New Britain
Health Department. "Once this information gets disseminated to places
like the methadone clinic, word of mouth will spread it pretty
quickly."
Health experts said they were concerned because a batch of heroin
made several people critically ill in New Jersey 2 weeks ago. 10
people who had snorted the drug showed up at hospitals in Warren,
Middlesex and Monmouth counties with the same symptoms, including
headaches and racing hearts.
Dr. Steven Marcus, executive director of the New Jersey Poison
Information and Education System said it was possible it all came
from the same place. He said he sent alerts to health departments
along the East Coast.
"It's still early in the investigation," Marcus said. "We're not 100
percent sure that it's all linked together."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In an earlier ProMED-mail posting (Cyanide poisoning, contaminated
heroin - USA (PA, NJ): alert 20050203.0371), cyanide was postulated
as the most likely contaminant in the heroin responsible for the
events in Pennsylvania and New Jersey. In the above Health Alert
from the New York City Department of Health & Mental Hygiene, there
is mention of identification of clenbuterol in some specimens, not
cyanide as previously suspected.
As mentioned above, clenbuterol is an illicit, long-acting beta
adrenergic agonist that is used primarily for increasing lean body
mass in cattle (note that its use in cattle is illicit and not an
accepted practice). People occasionally use clenbuterol as part of
exercise training to increase endurance and reduce body fat. There
have been reports of food poisoning associated with
clenbuterol-contaminated meat (see refs 1, 2, 3, 4). Similarly,
there have been case reports of toxicity associated with illicit use
in exercise training (see ref. 5 and 6 for reviews).
The above alert mentions probable cases in New Jersey, New York City,
Pennsylvania, and Connecticut, suggesting that the contamination of
heroin occurred prior to local distribution. It is possible that
other areas are also being affected by contaminated heroin if the
point of contamination was either prior to entry to the USA or
immediately after entry, before further distribution. ProMED-mail
would be interested to learn if compatible cases have been seen
outside of the northeast of the USA.
References:
1: Brambilla G, Cenci T, Franconi F, Galarini R, Macri A, Rondoni F,
Strozzi M, Loizzo A. Clinical and pharmacological profile in a
clenbuterol epidemic poisoning of contaminated beef meat in Italy.
Toxicol Lett. 2000 Apr 3;114(1-3):47-53.
2: Sporano V, Grasso L, Esposito M, Oliviero G, Brambilla G, Loizzo
A. Clenbuterol residues in non-liver containing meat as a cause of
collective food poisoning. Vet Hum Toxicol. 1998 Jun;40(3):141-3.
3: Salleras L, Dominguez A, Mata E, Taberner JL, Moro I, Salva P.
Epidemiologic study of an outbreak of clenbuterol poisoning in
Catalonia, Spain. Public Health Rep. 1995 May-Jun;110(3):338-42.
4: Bilbao Garay J, Hoyo Jimenez JF, Lopez Jimenez M, Vinuesa
Sebastian M, Perianes Matesanz J, Munoz Moreno P, Ruiz Galiana J.
[Clenbuterol poisoning. Clinical and analytical data on an outbreak
in Mostoles, Madrid] Rev Clin Esp. 1997 Feb;197(2):92-5.
5: Hoffman RJ, Hoffman RS, Freyberg CL, Poppenga RH, Nelson LS.
Clenbuterol ingestion causing prolonged tachycardia, hypokalemia, and
hypophosphatemia with confirmation by quantitative levels. J Toxicol
Clin Toxicol. 2001;39(4):339-44.
6: Chan TY. Food-borne clenbuterol may have potential for
cardiovascular effects with chronic exposure (commentary). J Toxicol
Clin Toxicol. 2001;39(4):345-8.
- Mod.MPP]
